CA1862.shortDescription: Используйте перегрузки метода "StringComparison" для сравнения строк без учета регистра
CA1862.fullDescription: Не вызывайте "ToLower", "ToUpper", "ToLowerInvariant" и "ToUpperInvariant" для сравнения строк без учета регистра, например, "string.ToLower() == string.ToLower()", поскольку это приведет к выделению. При переходе на использование перегрузки, которая использует "StringComparison", поведение может немного измениться, поэтому проведите тщательное тестирование после применения этой рекомендации. S101.shortDescription: Types should be named in PascalCase
S101.fullDescription: Shared naming conventions allow teams to collaborate efficiently.

S107.shortDescription: Methods should not have too many parameters
S107.fullDescription: Methods with a long parameter list are difficult to use because maintainers must figure out the role of each parameter and keep track of their position.

S1117.shortDescription: Local variables should not shadow class fields or properties
S1117.fullDescription: Shadowing occurs when a local variable has the same name as a variable, field, or property in an outer scope.

S1118.shortDescription: Utility classes should not have public constructors
S1118.fullDescription: Whenever there are portions of code that are duplicated and do not depend on the state of their container class, they can be centralized inside a "utility class". A utility class is a class that only has static members, hence it should not be instantiated.

S112.shortDescription: General or reserved exceptions should never be thrown
S112.fullDescription: This rule raises an issue when a general or reserved exception is thrown.

S1125.shortDescription: Boolean literals should not be redundant
S1125.fullDescription: A boolean literal can be represented in two different ways: true or false. They can be combined with logical operators (!, &&, ||, ==, !=) to produce logical expressions that represent truth values. However, comparing a boolean literal to a variable or expression that evaluates to a boolean value is unnecessary and can make the code harder to read and understand. The more complex a boolean expression is, the harder it will be for developers to understand its meaning and expected behavior, and it will favour the introduction of new bugs.

S1144.shortDescription: Unused private types or members should be removed
S1144.fullDescription: This rule raises an issue when a private/internal type or member is never referenced in the code.

S1192.shortDescription: String literals should not be duplicated
S1192.fullDescription: Duplicated string literals make the process of refactoring complex and error-prone, as any change would need to be propagated on all occurrences.

S1244.shortDescription: Floating point numbers should not be tested for equality
S1244.fullDescription: Floating point numbers in C# (and in most other programming languages) are not precise. They are a binary approximation of the actual value. This means that even if two floating point numbers appear to be equal, they might not be due to the tiny differences in their binary representation.

S125.shortDescription: Sections of code should not be commented out
S125.fullDescription: Commented-out code distracts the focus from the actual executed code. It creates a noise that increases maintenance code. And because it is never executed, it quickly becomes out of date and invalid.

S1481.shortDescription: Unused local variables should be removed
S1481.fullDescription: An unused local variable is a variable that has been declared but is not used anywhere in the block of code where it is defined. It is dead code, contributing to unnecessary complexity and leading to confusion when reading the code. Therefore, it should be removed from your code to maintain clarity and efficiency.

S1871.shortDescription: Two branches in a conditional structure should not have exactly the same implementation
S1871.fullDescription: When the same code is duplicated in two or more separate branches of a conditional, it can make the code harder to understand, maintain, and can potentially introduce bugs if one instance of the code is changed but others are not.

S2068.fullDescription: Because it is easy to extract strings from an application source code or binary, credentials should not be hard-coded. This is particularly true for applications that are distributed or that are open-source.

S2094.fullDescription: There is no good excuse for an empty class. If it’s being used simply as a common extension point, it should be replaced with an interface. If it was stubbed in as a placeholder for future development it should be fleshed-out. In any other case, it should be eliminated.

S2234.shortDescription: Arguments should be passed in the same order as the method parameters
S2234.fullDescription: Calling a method with argument variables whose names match the method parameter names but in a different order can cause confusion. It could indicate a mistake in the arguments' order, leading to unexpected results.

S2245.shortDescription: Using pseudorandom number generators (PRNGs) is security-sensitive
S2245.fullDescription: PRNGs are algorithms that produce sequences of numbers that only approximate true randomness. While they are suitable for applications like simulations or modeling, they are not appropriate for security-sensitive contexts because their outputs can be predictable if the internal state is known.

S2583.shortDescription: Conditionally executed code should be reachable
S2583.fullDescription: Conditional expressions which are always true or false can lead to unreachable code.

S2629.fullDescription: Logging arguments should not require evaluation in order to avoid unnecessary performance overhead. When passing concatenated strings or string interpolations directly into a logging method, the evaluation of these expressions occurs every time the logging method is called, regardless of the log level. This can lead to inefficient code execution and increased resource consumption.

S3459.fullDescription: Fields and auto-properties that are never assigned to hold the default values for their types. They are either pointless code or, more likely, mistakes.

S3903.shortDescription: Types should be defined in named namespaces
S3903.fullDescription: Types are declared in namespaces in order to prevent name collisions and as a way to organize them into the object hierarchy. Types that are defined outside any named namespace are in a global namespace that cannot be referenced in code.

S4136.shortDescription: Method overloads should be grouped together
S4136.fullDescription: For clarity, all overloads of the same method should be grouped together. That lets both users and maintainers quickly understand all the current available options.

S4144.shortDescription: Methods should not have identical implementations
S4144.fullDescription: Two methods having the same implementation are suspicious. It might be that something else was intended. Or the duplication is intentional, which becomes a maintenance burden.

S6418.fullDescription: Because it is easy to extract strings from an application source code or binary, secrets should not be hard-coded. This is particularly true for applications that are distributed or that are open-source.

S6444.shortDescription: Not specifying a timeout for regular expressions is security-sensitive
S6444.fullDescription: Not specifying a timeout for regular expressions can lead to a Denial-of-Service attack. Pass a timeout when using System.Text.RegularExpressions to process untrusted input because a malicious user might craft a value for which the evaluation lasts excessively long.

S6667.shortDescription: Logging in a catch clause should pass the caught exception as a parameter.
S6667.fullDescription: This rule raises an issue on logging calls inside a catch clause that does not pass the raised Exception.

S6781.shortDescription: JWT secret keys should not be disclosed
S6781.fullDescription: Secret leaks often occur when a sensitive piece of authentication data is stored with the source code of an application. Considering the source code is intended to be deployed across multiple assets, including source code repositories or application hosting servers, the secrets might get exposed to an unintended audience.

S6960.shortDescription: Controllers should not have mixed responsibilities
S6960.fullDescription: ASP.NET controllers should not have mixed responsibilities. Following the Single Responsibility Principle (SRP), they should be kept lean and focused on a single, separate concern. In short, they should have a single reason to change.

S6962.shortDescription: You should pool HTTP connections with HttpClientFactory
S6962.fullDescription: In frequently used code paths, such as controller actions, you should avoid using the HttpClient directly and opt for one of the IHttpClientFactory-based mechanisms instead. This way, you avoid wasting resources and creating performance overhead.

S6964.shortDescription: Value type property used as input in a controller action should be nullable, required or annotated with the JsonRequiredAttribute to avoid under-posting.
S6964.fullDescription: "Under-posting" refers to a situation where a client sends less data than expected to the server during an HTTP request, for example when the client omits some properties from the request body that the server expects to receive.

S6966.fullDescription: In an async method, any blocking operations should be avoided.

S927.shortDescription: Parameter names should match base declaration and other partial definitions
S927.fullDescription: Parameters are part of the method signature and its identity.
